text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: Accent Discrimination in Technology%0a:Author: david_h%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 01.05.2021 - 13:34%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-222647-639650#%0a* [-11.05.2021 - 15:26-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-222647-639650#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAmazon Alexa and Google Home are unable to understand some accents more than others.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe following article from the Washington Post shows that even technology can discriminate against specific accents: https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/business/alexa-does-not-understand-your-accent/%0a%0aWhile the discrimination is not as intentional as other examples, the fact is that these technologies rely on datasets of people's accents. If the voice recognition service is trained on "standard accents" then it is implicitly discriminating against "non-standard accents". As such, accents of immigrants are the hardest for Google and Alexa to understand. The study found that Spanish and Chinese accents consistently scored the lowest in Alexa and Google understandability.%0a%0aThe article shows how a news headline is interpreted by Alexa differently depending on the accent of the speaker. With standard American English, it was able to detect "trump bulldozed fox news host showing again why he likes phone injuries" which is correct except for "injuries" (interviews). However, when a nonnative English speaker spoke, Alexa detected it as "from bulldozed of fox new house showing again why lights phone interview". This makes it almost impossible for nonnative English speakers, specifically those with Chinese or Spanish accents to use these voice assistants.%0a%0aThe solution is not easy. Since there are so many variations in nonnative English speech as compared to standard American English, engineers at Google and Amazon as well as linguists working with these technologies, it is harder to train the speakers to recognize these accents. A study found a correlation between diversity in voice data and being able to understand more accents. Since the dataset is not diverse enough when it comes to nonnative English accents, the speakers were not able to recognize them.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
